:: AI Ethics Codex {"position":"1250,750","size":"100,100"}
<h2>AI Ethics Codex</h2>
<div class="explanation">
A summary of the core principles you've learned. Use this to guide your decisions.
</div>

---
<h3>Key Principles</h3>
<b>Fairness & Inclusiveness:</b><br>
Ensuring that AI systems do not create or perpetuate unfair biases against individuals or groups, especially vulnerable populations. Systems should be designed for equitable outcomes.

<b>Transparency & Explainability (XAI):</b><br>
The inner workings of an AI system should be understandable to human operators. An AI should be able to explain why it made a particular decision, especially in high-stakes situations.

<b>Accountability:</b><br>
Establishing clear responsibility for the outcomes of an AI system. If an AI causes harm, there must be a framework to determine who is liable—the developer, the user, or the operator.

<b>Privacy & Data Minimization:</b><br>
Protecting individual privacy by collecting only the data that is strictly necessary for a specific purpose and ensuring that data is stored securely.

<b>Human Control & Oversight:</b><br>
Ensuring that humans can intervene and take control of AI systems, especially in critical scenarios. Full automation is not always the most ethical choice.

---
<br>
